<section xml:id="properties-exponential-functions">
    <title>The Properties of Exponential Functions</title>
        <theorem xml:id="thm-exponential-functions-a-gt-1">
            <title>Exponential Functions with <m>a &gt; 1</m></title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>f(x) = a^x</m> be an exponential function where <m>a &gt; 1</m>. The graph of <m>f</m> has the following properties:
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Domain: <m>\left( -\infty, \infty \right)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Range: <m>\left( 0, \infty \right)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>y</m>-intercept: <m>(0, 1)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                End Behavior:
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            As <m>x \to \infty, f(x) \to \infty</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            As <m>x \to -\infty, f(x) \to 0</m>. This implies the <m>x</m>-axis is a horizontal asymptote.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The function is increasing on <m>\left( -\infty, \infty \right)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-graph-exp-a-gt-1">
                        <caption>The graph of <m>f(x) = a^x</m> where <m>a &gt; 1</m>. 
                            The sample points <m>(-2, \frac{1}{a^2})</m>, <m>(-1, \frac{1}{a})</m>, <m>(0, 1)</m>, <m>(1, a)</m>, and <m>(2, a^2)</m> are plotted.</caption>
                            <image source="chapter-8/graph-exp-a-gt-1.png" width="50%" decorative="yes"/>
                    </figure>   
            </statement>
        </theorem>
        <example xml:id="example-graph-exp-a-gt-1">
            <title>Graphing an Exponential Function with <m>a &gt; 1</m></title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Graph <m>f(x) = 2^x</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <figure xml:id="fig-graph-exp-2-x">
                    <caption>The graph of <m>f(x) = 2^x</m>. 
                        The sample points <m>(-2, \frac{1}{4})</m>, <m>(-1, \frac{1}{2})</m>, <m>(0, 1)</m>, <m>(1, 2)</m>, and <m>(2, 4)</m> are plotted.</caption>
                        <image source="chapter-8/graph-exp-2-x.png" width="50%" decorative="yes"/>
                </figure>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    As long as you know your powers of the base and the properties of exponential functions, you can plot points and sketch the graph of any rational function.
                    The following table gives some sample points for when <m>a=2</m>
                </p>
                <table>
                    <title>Sample Points for <m>f(x)=2^x</m></title>
                    <tabular>
                        <row header="yes">
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>2^x</m></cell>
                            <cell>Point</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\frac{1}{4}</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\left( -2, \frac{1}{4} \right)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\frac{1}{2}</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\left( -1, \frac{1}{2} \right)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(0, 1)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(1, 2)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(2, 4)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>First, we plot these five points on the coordinate plane.</p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-graph-exp-2-x-points-only">
                    <caption>The sample points <m>(-2, \frac{1}{4})</m>, <m>(-1, \frac{1}{2})</m>, <m>(0, 1)</m>, <m>(1, 2)</m>, and <m>(2, 4)</m> plotted on the coordinate plane.</caption>
                    <image source="chapter-8/graph-exp-2-x-points.png" width="50%" decorative="yes"/>
                </figure>
                <p>Next, we draw a curve through the points, making sure the graph will approach but never reach the <m>x</m>-axis as <m>x\rightarrow -\infty</m>.</p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-graph-exp-2-x-complete">
                    <caption>The graph of <m>f(x) = 2^x</m> and its sample points <m>(-2, \frac{1}{4})</m>, <m>(-1, \frac{1}{2})</m>, <m>(0, 1)</m>, <m>(1, 2)</m>, and <m>(2, 4)</m> are plotted.</caption>
                        <image source="chapter-8/graph-exp-2-x.png" width="50%" decorative="yes"/>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <theorem xml:id="thm-exponential-functions-a-lt-1">
            <title>Exponential Functions with <m>0 &lt; a &lt; 1</m></title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>f(x) = a^x</m> be an exponential function where <m>0 &lt; a &lt; 1</m>. The graph of <m>f</m> has the following properties:
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Domain: <m>\left( -\infty, \infty \right)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Range: <m>\left( 0, \infty \right)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>y</m>-intercept: <m>(0, 1)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                End Behavior:
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            As <m>x \to \infty, f(x) \to 0</m>. This implies the <m>x</m>-axis is a horizontal asymptote.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            As <m>x \to -\infty, f(x) \to \infty</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The function is decreasing on <m>\left( -\infty, \infty \right)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-graph-exp-a-lt-1">
                        <caption>The graph of <m>f(x) = a^x</m> where <m>0 &lt; a &lt; 1</m>. 
                            The sample points <m>(-2, \frac{1}{a^2})</m>, <m>(-1, \frac{1}{a})</m>, <m>(0, 1)</m>, <m>(1, a)</m>, and <m>(2, a^2)</m> are plotted.</caption>
                            <image source="chapter-8/graph-exp-a-lt-1.png" width="50%" decorative="yes"/>
                    </figure>   
            </statement>
        </theorem>
        <example xml:id="example-graph-exp-2-negx">
